This implies \( f(1) + n \) must be divisible by \( 1 + f(n) \). For \( m = 2 \), this implies \( 5 \mid 2 f(2) + 1 \), leading to \( f(2) = 2 \). 3. **General Case**: - For each \( n \), \( f(n) + 1 \) must divide \( n + 1 \). Thus, the only function \( f \) that satisfies the given condition is the identity function \( f(n) = n \). \[ \boxed{f(n) = n} \]
